          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Houthis strike Israeli airport</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/houthi-projectile-near-ben-gurion-airport-israel-inspection.png" alt="Israeli security forces inspect the site where a projectile fired by Yemen's Houthi rebels landed, near Ben Gurion Airpor" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Israeli security forces inspect the site where a projectile fired by Yemen's Houthi rebels landed, near Ben Gurion Airport. Credits: Ohad Zwigenberg/AP</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Despite interception attempts by Israel’s Arrow interceptor and the US-deployed THAAD, a Houthi-fired hypersonic <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-may-25-spotlight-h2-3-missile-struck-near-ben-gurion-airport" target="_blank">missile struck near Ben Gurion Airport</a>. The rebel group called it a response to Israel’s measures in Gaza and warned of “comprehensive air blockade” by targeting airports. This is the first time the group has targeted Israel’s airport. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The incident stopped flights and train services, leading major airlines to pause travel to Tel Aviv. Israeli leaders promised a swift reply. PM Netanyahu called for further measures, and Defense Minister Katz warned of a “sevenfold” retaliation. Israel’s security cabinet convened on Sunday afternoon to discuss the incident. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Military experts are worried about missile defenses against threats like hypersonic missiles. Meanwhile, Hamas has praised the attack and called Yemen, “a twin of Palestine.” Sunday’s strike marks the third consecutive day of missile launches from Yemen toward Israel. </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="0px 12px" />
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
    <!-- Content sections -->
    <mj-section css-class="mj_section" background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">India-Pakistan cold war tactics</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: While the Pahalgam attack has riled up India and Pakistan, their future approaches differ.</strong></p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          A terrorist attack in Pahalgam, Indian-administered Kashmir, killed 26 tourists, reigniting tensions between nuclear-armed India and Pakistan. The Indian government is under pressure to retaliate forcefully, with calls for an Israel-style military response. The incident also raises questions about the revocation of <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-may-25-spotlight-h3-4-article-370" target="_blank">Article 370</a>, which removed Kashmir’s self-governing status.
        </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          If it enters a full-scale war, <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-may-25-spotlight-h3-5-india-risks-derailing-its-economic-goals" target="_blank">India risks derailing its economic goals</a>, like becoming a $5 trillion economy. Though Prime Minister Narendra Modi has given the military autonomy, India is expected to rely on targeted operations instead. The broader strategy involves pressuring Pakistan into internal collapse rather than escalating outright conflict.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Pakistan sees a strategic possibility in the crisis. India’s tough stance has fueled anti-India sentiment, uniting political factions. Pakistan has moved troops and air defense systems closer to the Line of Control. It also condemned India’s suspension of the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-may-25-spotlight-h3-6-indus-water-treaty" target="_blank">Indus Water Treaty</a>, using it to stoke Islamic and nationalist sentiment.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Despite its rhetoric, Pakistan’s weak economy limits its war capacity. It will likely continue with provocations rather than a full conflict. India, aware of the high expenses, will maintain a restrained response, recognizing that escalation could lead to a long stalemate.</p>
        </mj-text>
